"Nogué S., Rull V., Vegas-Vilarrúbia T.","Modeling biodiversity loss by global warming on Pantepui, northern South America: Projected upward migration and potential habitat loss",2009,"Climatic Change","94","1-2",,"77","85",,,10.1007/s10584-009-9554-x,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-67349209498&partnerID=40&md5=b5defbf2b51a78529d1d54f376870f15","Departament de Biologia Animal, Biologia Vegetal i Ecologia, Facultat de Biociències, Universitat Autònoma de Barcelona, C1-227, Bellaterra, Barcelona 08193, Spain; CSIC-Botanic Institute of Barcelona, Palynology and Paleoecology, Pg. del Migdia s/n, Barcelona 08038, Spain; Departament d'Ecologia, Universitat de Barcelona, Av. Diagonal 645, Barcelona 08028, Spain","Nogué, S., Departament de Biologia Animal, Biologia Vegetal i Ecologia, Facultat de Biociències, Universitat Autònoma de Barcelona, C1-227, Bellaterra, Barcelona 08193, Spain; Rull, V., CSIC-Botanic Institute of Barcelona, Palynology and Paleoecology, Pg. del Migdia s/n, Barcelona 08038, Spain; Vegas-Vilarrúbia, T., Departament d'Ecologia, Universitat de Barcelona, Av. Diagonal 645, Barcelona 08028, Spain","This work aims to estimate the potential effects of the global warming projected for the twenty-first century on the biodiversity of a remote and pristine region of the Neotropics called Pantepui. Habitat loss and fragmentation by upward migration of bioclimatic conditions is analyzed using Species-Area Relationships (SAR) and Altitudinal Range Displacement (ARD) analysis. The ARD is a tool that uses the present-day lapse rate to estimate the upward migration of the species based on the global warming predicted by the IPCC. The results show that around 80% of the vascular flora, ca. 1,700 species of which up to 400 would be Pantepui endemics, are threatened of extinction. These estimates should be considered preliminary, but the danger is real. Therefore, suitable conservation or mitigation strategies are needed. © 2009 Springer Science+Business Media B.V.",,"Biodiversity loss; Habitat loss; Lapse rates; Mitigation strategies; Neotropics; Potential effects; Potential habitats; South america; Species-area relationships; Ecology; Forestry; Global warming; Ocean habitats; Biodiversity; biodiversity; endemic species; extinction; global warming; habitat fragmentation; habitat loss; migration; mitigation; South America",,,,,,"Araujo, M.B., Pearson, R.G., Thuiller, W., Erhard, M., Validation of species-climate impact models under climate change (2005) Global Change Biology, 11 (9), pp. 1504-1513. , DOI 10.1111/j.1365-2486.2005.01000.x; Berry, P.E., Riina, R., Insights into the diversity of the Pantepui flora and the biogeographic complexity of the Guayana Shield (2005) Biol Skr, 55, pp. 145-167; Bowman, W., Huber, U., Bugmann, H., Reasoner, M., The response of alpine plants to environmental change. Feedbacks to ecosystem function (2005) Global Change and Mountain Regions. An Overview of Current Knowledge, pp. 377-382. , Springer Dordrecht; Briceño, H.O., Schubert, C., Geomorphology of the Gran Sabana, Guayana Shield, southeastern Venezuela (1990) Geomorphology, 3, pp. 125-141; Clubbe, C., Blackmore, R., Reddish, A., Threats to biodiversity (1996) Global Environmental Issues, pp. 129-237. , Hodder and Stoughton London; Dirnbock, T., Dullinger, S., Grabherr, G., A regional impact assessment of climate and land-use change on alpine vegetation (2003) Journal of Biogeography, 30 (3), pp. 401-417; Ebenman, B., Jonsson, T., Using community viability analysis to identify fragile systems and keystone species (2005) Trends in Ecology and Evolution, 20 (10), pp. 568-575. , DOI 10.1016/j.tree.2005.06.011, PII S016953470500203X; Edmond, J.M., Palmer, M.R., Measures, C.I., Grant, B., Stallard, R.F., The fluvial geochemistry and denudation rate of the Guayana Shield in Venezuela, Colombia, and Brazil (1995) Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta, 59 (16), pp. 3301-3325. , DOI 10.1016/0016-7037(95)00128-M; Foster, P., The potential